<!-- spacer --></td><td width="10"><img width="10" height="1" src="images/space.gif" alt=""></td></tr></table>
<table bgcolor="#000000" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td width="10"><img width="10" height="1" src="images/space.gif" alt=""></td><td width="100%"><!-- spacer -->

<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#000000"  width="100%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#303070" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post164040"></a>
	
	<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" ><b>synnoira</b></font><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Mwahahaha</font><br>
	<p>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Registered: Mar 2002<br>
<!--	Location: <br>
	Posts: 2052-->
</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#303070" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" ><img src="images/icons/icon1.gif" border="0" alt=""> <b></b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >The weapons and shield stuff sounds fine. Variety is the spice of life and in so far as logic helps immersion in a magical world making shields enhance defensive abilities in some manner makes sense. There was talk of shields giving a block skill of some sort a while back before PoP so the idea has been looked at i think.<br />
<br />
For the archery changes, i'm not sure i like the idea of interrupts when moving. From a purely selfish perspective i use archery to pull and am usually moving when the arrow fires. I guess you're seeing that as a PvP change? I think i'd take the harsh line that it's a PvE game, design for that and patch up any PvP issues later.<br />
<br />
Bringing throwing up to par for monks and rogues seems entirely fair. Why do knights need throwing though? That seems to be unnecessary blurring between classes.<br />
<br />
The aggro changes you have are where i really part company. What's the purpose behind adding a zero second stun to EB weapons? If the problem is one of itemization for low end warriors that solves nothing, and i'm not seeing aggro problems for the high end warriors who have them (and we haven't done RZ either so the guys i see are slumming it with BoC's, etc). It seems to me high end warrior aggro is at the ceiling where any improvement risks trivialising aggro management.<br />
<br />
I think the problem with warriors is that while other classes have become diversified (much to their benefit), warriors remain locked into doing one single job in all situations. Unfortunately a lot of players are still fixed on the idea that "class balance" means that each class has a "class-defining ablility" and must be "king of" something or other. It doesn't work, and particularly doesn't work well in a game where the combat engine asks for one single tank. You could make warriors the most uber tanks and taunters, but if he's not the main tank he's just a spare wheel. They try to solve this problem by throwing adds into every encounter they can, but then you've got sk's/paladins jockeying for those jobs too. And it's no help to the low end warrior who is still damn all use to a group if he's not the main tank. <br />
<br />
The idea of toggling on and off different "stances" has been around for a bit. Hook them up to the stamina bar for a warrior and make it meaningful for them much as mana is for a knight. Additionally basic melee utility skills Forage, Hide, etc should all be available to warriors as trained combatants. Not going to get them groups of course, but i'm fed up hearing blether about "you get to invis". <br />
<br />
If a warrior isn't tanking what could he do? I think one option is to expand on the concept of Warcry and give some different varieties. Perhaps an extra haste bard-style, different immunities to certain spell types, enhanced avoidance for the group. Make them all available but based on the stamina bar. They'd be things the warrior could bring to the party which would allow him to enhance it's effectiveness, much as say LoH, or HT, or various spell abilities allow a paladin or sk to do even though they may not be the tank. It's my limited understanding that EQOA has pursued this sort of concept.<br />
<br />
The other melee classes are not in as dire need of a retooling if you ask me (begging the pardon of sundry posters at MB and the Safehouse). Rogues could use poisons all being store-bought and i hate the idea of a class which has a tradeskill incorporated into it's design but rogues i know swear by poisons. I'm aware they  may be highly eccentric. The monks i know have kept happily trucking through all the fuss. I think giving those classes range damage as suggested is correct, but beyond that i'm unconvinced they've got anything like the problems some would have you believe. And as things are i don't really see any need for more hybrid disciplines since our spells now generally pick up the slack. Not that i'd turn them down, and it would be very nice if Leechcurse was on a 15 minute timer (as Synd used to have on his list). Paladins are worst off for discs, but i don't see them lacking in what they bring to the party at the moment.<br />
<br />
Overall i'd say like the weapon stuff, etc but rather sceptical of tampering around with aggro.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >__________________<br>
Synnoira Reddhand<br />
Dread Lord of Travelers of Norrath Saryrn</font></p></p>
