	<td bgcolor="#404070" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" ><img src="images/icons/icon1.gif" border="0" alt=""> <b></b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >Sorry.. long.. lots of replies!<br />
<br />
QUOTE<br />
Darko<br />
  <br />
I like the direction you heading, however i think such huge damage/mitigation changes at this point in the game would trivalize too much current content. <br />
<br />
If a warrior could stack a second defensive type disc on top of defensive, keep agro, and get added parry/rip from shield all at once, sony would have to seriosly beef up most pop mobs to keep things chalenging.<br />
END QUOTE<br />
<br />
<br />
Note, that I specifically stated that the greater disciplines and old disciplines had separate timers...  but I also mentioned that you could only EVER have one discipline active.  thus if you were using the permanent one, you could NOT be using the old /defensive.<br />
<br />
You can already Parry/Riposte anyways you just get an extra roll if you have a shield readied...  note, since you DO have a shield readied, you are dealing less damage... and thus less taunt...  its a tradeoff.<br />
<br />
We both know mobs in PoP are strong buggers...  We both know its not really an issue.<br />
<br />
I DO see an issue with the innate defense and /defensive....  perhaps a reduction in the effectiveness of the current /disc defensive in trade for the innate changes for warriors. (they could also remove a proportional amount of the offensive penalty to /disc defensive)<br />
<br />
<br />
QUOTE<br />
And on a final note, knights/warriors are on the same tank table atm, the only advantage warriors have over us is higher ripo/dodge/parry caps, more hp and discs.<br />
END QUOTE<br />
<br />
I think everyone is on the same tank table... wouldnt it make sense for Knights and to a greater extent warriors to have their own tables?  The idea is to improve that.<br />
      <br />
 <br />
 <br />
QUOTE  <br />
Mardark<br />
  <br />
Too complicated, needs to be simple.<br />
<br />
Knights - Increase weapon skills to 240.<br />
<br />
Add AA's to increase melee dmg at end game even more (or just increase effect of current AA's).<br />
<br />
Change AA's affecting 2h to affect both 2h and 1h.<br />
<br />
Add dmg bonus to off hand for dual wield.<br />
<br />
Rescale Dmg bonuses so you arent penalized as much for short delay weapons. Two weapons of the same ratio, should do the same dmg no matter what level you are at.<br />
END QUOTE<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I would argue that frankly, the solutions should not require additional AAXP.  I would also rather outline good solutions than give them overly simple ones that result in knee-jerks. (monk debacle, 2H changes STILL not resolved, dual wield phase-out, etc...<br />
 <br />
 <br />
<br />
QUOTE  <br />
synnoira<br />
<br />
<snip agreed parts><br />
<br />
For the archery changes, i'm not sure i like the idea of interrupts when moving. From a purely selfish perspective i use archery to pull and am usually moving when the arrow fires. I guess you're seeing that as a PvP change? I think i'd take the harsh line that it's a PvE game, design for that and patch up any PvP issues later.<br />
<br />
Bringing throwing up to par for monks and rogues seems entirely fair. Why do knights need throwing though? That seems to be unnecessary blurring between classes.<br />
<br />
The aggro changes you have are where i really part company. What's the purpose behind adding a zero second stun to EB weapons? If the problem is one of itemization for low end warriors that solves nothing, and i'm not seeing aggro problems for the high end warriors who have them (and we haven't done RZ either so the guys i see are slumming it with BoC's, etc). It seems to me high end warrior aggro is at the ceiling where any improvement risks trivialising aggro management.<br />
END QUOTE<br />
<br />
<br />
We get throwing because of the changes to archery....  you could have archery's functional equivalent by using throwing...  Throwing would have a couple advantages 1) instant 2) point blank with no penalty. (1H damage bonus only, and lower damage than bows however.)  Trade off.<br />
<br />
Aggro changes are to NERF EB.  Warriors are getting an ability that allows the average joe without EB to cause more hate (kick changes)  0 second stun allows some effect that is useful for those that have it above the hate changes.  The idea is to make EB weapons optional for warriors.  0 second stun also gives some "take notice" effect to the +hate stuff....  Just use our hate line and see how terrible Terrors are for attention getting. (great once you have it, but terrible to GET it)  This is an overall nerf for warriors for EB and an improvment for us.  The oevrall effect is warriors taunt better without EB, and EB gets the nerf stick, and our hate line has a use outside taking up spellbook space.<br />
<br />
 <br />
QUOTE <br />
lorddaeth<br />
<br />
while many of your suggestions are good in thought, they do not take the whole scope into play.<br />
<br />
any change to warrior abilities will only trivialize encounters further. period. <br />
END QUOTE<br />
<br />
<br />
Read the first objection to it...  PoP mobs trivial my patootie... they still eat full elemental equipped warriors in NO time without proper Cheal chains.  In that case, who the heck cares if a warrior is 10-15% better at absorbing damage AVERAGE) than normal.  The CHs can be another .5 second apart! (yay)<br />
<br />
The whole scope is relative mob difficulty as well... they need to add a few mobs here and there for certain encounters... but we both know unit for unit that the mobs are friggin rediculously powerful in comparison to a player characters.<br />
<br />
You are too used to being a wuss compared to the mobs...  put a caster vs a snareable/rootable dark blue mob...  now put a melee against a similar mob....  the melee goes splat...  this is not really fair.<br />
<br />
We aren't talking enormous changes in the balance of mobs vs characters... we are talking a slight shift for the characters.<br />
<br />
In partial elemental gear, I can go back to Luclin and pick a dark blue mob (barely dark blue though) and solo him face to face...  this is only due to my caster side and lifetaps....  have a warrior do the same thing with no outside help...  you will be running.  Im sorry, thats wrong.  Masters of melee combat should be pretty dang tough...  WE shouldn't be pushovers either... (I hate playing necro in PoP dagnabbit.)<br />
<br />
Casters can pick anything they have mana to solo that doesn't summon and is snareable...  why is it melees are so handicapped?<br />
<br />
Brik</font></p>
	
